	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Ghanaian tuna conquers the Nigerian market</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> StarKist premium canned tuna, produced and manufactured in Ghana, was officially launched on the Nigerian market on December 19th 2004. StarKist fish products have been available in most supermarkets and open markets for several years and the company has an increasing number of catering institutions using them in their regular meal service.</p><p> StarKist's relationship with Africa goes back as far as 1964 when Ghana was used as a base for the procurement of raw material. Just after that, in 1963, Heinz purchased the StarKist Company which quickly became the leading brand in the USA, a position it has held from that day. Interestingly, the US market used to be dominated by sardines, as is the case of Nigeria today, but tuna has now completely taken over. In 1976 StarKist's relationship with Ghana progressed with a partnership with a local Ghanaian company canning tuna for export, and it also now has over 70% of the Ghanaian market.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/200412201061.html" target="_self">Press article in <i>This Day</i>, Lagos, December 19th 2004</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.icsf.net/jsp/english/pubPages/reports/market.jsp" target="_self">Report of the study on problems and prospects of artisanal fish trade in...</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> This provides an interesting example of an ACP regional market being opened up for canned tuna produced in a neighbouring ACP country, where the product is subject to intense competition to access international markets. ACP regional markets may well offer interesting alternatives for other fishery products that are finding it increasingly difficult to access international markets (like the EU), due to the development of non-tariff barriers.</p><p> It is therefore strategically important for ACP countries, when considering the future prospects for the exploitation and marketing of their fish resources, that a full appraisal is made of the potential of developing regional ACP markets. These may well prove much more readily accessible, and even as lucrative as the EU market.</p><p> Such a strategy pre-supposes that a genuinely free circulation of persons and goods exists between ACP countries. However, currently there are several factors that make this difficult:</p>
<ul>

<li>poorly developed transport and communication infrastructures; </li>

<li>stringent border controls, incompatible with the perishable nature of fish; </li>

<li>problems of securing payment, particularly when countries belong to different monetary systems, and exchange rates may be set in an arbitrary fashion; </li>

<li>corruption.</li>

</ul>
<p> These are issues that ACP countries need to resolve urgently in order to maximise the potential benefits from regional ACP markets, and to provide some viable alternative markets for their fishery products. With market access to the EU increasingly restricted by non-tariff barriers, ACP countries need to develop such viable alternatives.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
